<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-146-994  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 146 994.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Feb 13 1990 v4 n6 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Claris steps into database credibility gap. (editorial)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Claris Corp. (product development).andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Data Base AdministrationProduct DevelopmentStructured Query LanguageData Manipulation LanguagesInformation Resources ManagementAcquisitionTechnology.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Claris steps into database credibility gapandM;It is well-known that the Macintosh has been a disappointment as a databaseplatform, selling far fewer units for this mainstream personal computerapplication than would be expected from its overall market share.andM;That's why there is a credibility gap when Apple and various third partiespromote the Mac as an ideal front end for corporate information systems -- bydefinition database applications.andP;  If corporations won't buy Macs forlocalized database applications, why should we expect them to turn to Macsfor infinitely more complex systems involving mainframes, minis anddistributed networks?andM;Last week Claris Corp. sought to fill the credibility gap by articulating astrategy positioning many of its products as information-management tools.andO;The occasion was the company's technology-acquisition announcement of a SQLquery tool, but the message had much deeper implications.andM;Claris believes the Mac has faltered as a database-transaction engine, butthat it can excel as a tool for database analysis and decision support.andO;Therefore, the company will market future products for browsing through andmanipulating corporate data.andM;These will be distinct from its offerings for the traditional databasemarket.andP;  For example, the query tool that Claris will eventually release as aproduct will not be part of Claris' market-leading database, FileMaker, but astand-alone module for ad hoc browsing through remote databases.andM;The company didn't say so, but it may pursue a similar strategy with the codefor Wingz that it recently purchased from Informix.andP;  Don't look for acomprehensive graphical spreadsheet.andP;  Instead, expect individual modules withspecific functionality for data-driven graphics, user scripting andstripped-down spreadsheet analysis.andM;Like ad hoc database browsing, each of these capabilities is a useful tool ina decision-support system.andP;  Using System 7.0 capabilities forinterapplication communications and AppleScript, MIS departments will be ableto put together custom decision-support systems matched to the individualneeds of their corporate data environments.andM;So far, this is all talk based on unannounced products and undelivered systemtools.andP;  Still, by articulating an information-management strategy, Claris isshowing how a credibility gap can be turned into a Macintosh advantage.andO;</TEXT></DOC>